      <h3>Our Verdict: Pause and Consult Your OB-GYN</h3>
      <p><strong>The current evidence does not support routine creatine supplementation during pregnancy or breastfeeding</strong> — not because creatine is known to be harmful, but because the safety database for supplemental doses in human pregnancy is genuinely insufficient. The conservative, widely-recommended approach is to pause supplementation when pregnancy is confirmed, continue normal dietary intake from meat and fish, and resume after weaning.</p>
      <p>If you have specific circumstances that make creatine important to you during pregnancy (athletic training, vegetarian diet with low baseline creatine, family history of perinatal complications), bring those to your OB-GYN for individualized guidance. Both continuation and pause are defensible positions depending on individual circumstances.</p>
      <p>For women who are not currently pregnant, the safety profile of creatine is excellent — see our companion guide on <a href="/blog/should-women-take-creatine/">should women take creatine</a> for the broader benefits review.</p>
